article.description: Betty Lennox scored 16 points as the Miami Sol set franchise records for total points, margin of victory and field-goal percentage in an 86-61 victory over the Phoenix Mercury on Wednesday night.
article.headline: Sol set franchise records in romp over Phoenix
article.linkText: Sol set team marks for points, win margin in romp over Mercury
article.story:
MIAMI (AP) -- Betty Lennox scored 16 points as the Miami Sol set franchise records for total points, margin of victory and field-goal percentage in an 86-61 victory over the Phoenix Mercury on Wednesday night. Pollyanna Johns Kimbrough shot 7-for-7 from the field and scored 14 points, and Sheri Sam also scored 14 for the Sol (5-9), who have won three straight. "We've known that we have a lot of talent on this team,'' Sam said. "We see it everyday in practice. It was just a matter of bringing it all to a game.'' Sandy Brondello added 11 for Miami, which shot a franchise-best 55.7 percent from the field. The Sol also matched franchise records with 25 assists, led by Debbie Black's seven, and seven 3-pointers, led by Lennox's 4-for-5 performance. "I'm thrilled with the win,'' Miami coach Ron Rothstein said. "I'm thrilled with the way we're playing.'' Jennifer Gillom shot 3-for-14 from the floor and had 12 points for Phoenix (7-7), which has lost four of its last five. Kayte Christensen added 11 points for the Mercury, who have been outscored by an average of 23.5 points in their last two games. "In my six years with the Mercury, I've never been in two back-to-back games more embarrassing than these,'' Gillom said. "It's kind of scary. We can't let this happen again.'' The Sol's previous franchise high for points was 78, and the team had never won by more than 20 points. Miami outscored Phoenix 41-12 during one stretch, including a 15-0 second-half run that gave the Sol a 65-29 lead with 10:38 remaining. The 36-point lead was the largest ever held by the Sol in franchise history. Phoenix answered with 10 consecutive points to get back within 65-39, but the Mercury still could not avoid matching the largest margin of defeat in their six-year history. The Mercury are 0-4 on the road this season and are winless in their last 10 road games dating to last July 27. "I don't know what the answer is,'' Phoenix coach Linda Sharp. "We've got two nights before going to Orlando to find it.'' All seven of the Sol's previous games at home this season were decided by nine points or less, and Miami was 2-5 in those contests.

Game notes
Miami entered as the lowest-scoring team in the WNBA, at 63.2 ppg. ... All 11 Miami players scored. ... Black, the WNBA's assist-to-turnover leader by a wide margin, has 57 assists and 10 turnovers this season. Black's last three games have been turnover-free. ... The Sol have not scored more than 39 first-half points in any game this season. ... The Mercury are 1-3 since Cynthia Cooper resigned as coach on June 25. ... Christensen's eight rebounds were a game high.
